istory that Hollywood often references in amicus briefs, like the one=20
( http://sblog.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/AmicusMPAA.09-14=
48.pdf?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F2%2F24%29&=
utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F4%2F24%29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) =
15 years ago when California attempted to restrict the sale of violent vide=
o games to minors.

Amicus briefs
are also valuable when the case=E2=80=99s primary party lacks widespread sy=
mpathy. While few may empathize with ByteDance and its Chinese government p=
uppeteers, reminding American jurists that the domestic entertainment indus=
try has a stake in this outcome would highlight the overarching importance =
of the First Amendment. Plus, it isn=E2=80=99t even necessary to support Ti=
kTok. One can argue for the TikTok creators who have filed their own legal =
challenge. And if that=E2=80=99s still too much, anyone can file an amicus =
brief, technically supporting neither side, but stating some interest nonet=
heless.

Hollywood=E2=80=99s decision to remain on the sideline stems in part from a=
 general unease about the Chinese government, who controls the TikTok algor=
ithm, and how ByteDance is or isn=E2=80=99t safeguarding user data. Just as=
 some executives might legitimately think twice before downloading the app =
onto their personal phones, there=E2=80=99s a palpable discomfort in rallyi=
ng around the free speech
rights of a company under suspicion=E2=80=94especially one whose ownership =
is based in a country that bans American apps and movies without a second t=
hought. Also: Just because we don=E2=80=99t know the precise basis for the =
Biden administration=E2=80=99s national security concerns doesn=E2=80=99t m=
ean they=E2=80=99re unfounded.

Based on my conversations, however, Hollywood=E2=80=99s reluctance to speak=
 up for TikTok may have as much to do with old-fashioned rivalry. The app=
=E2=80=99s explosive growth and low overhead is capturing the youth demo th=
at the entertainment industry covets. And despite increased lobbying, TikTo=
k hasn=E2=80=99t built strong alliances, or supported others in their polit=
ical and legal fights, rendering it somewhat of an outsider.

The perspective that TikTok is less friend than foe might change. Not long =
ago, Google was enemy number one for movie studios, which encouraged ( http=
s://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/17/technology/googles-critics-enlist-state-atto=
rneys-general-in-their-fight.html?smid=3Dnytcore-ios-share&referringSource=
=3DarticleShare&sgrp=3Dc-cb&utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%287%2F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286=
%2F4%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3D=
f6c60617da42abd12a ) attorneys general across the country to investigate th=
e web giant for not doing more to censor illegal content. Recently, however=
, the MPA signed an amicus brief=20
( https://www.motionpictures.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/12.5.23-RCFP-Ne=
tChoice-v.-Paxton-PDF-A.pdf?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%287%2F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286=
%2F4%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3D=
f6c60617da42abd12a ) objecting to states like Texas and Florida targeting d=
igital platforms, like Google=E2=80=99s YouTube, for moderating content. In=
cidentally, that very case, Netchoice v. Paxton, was decided ( https://www.=
supremecourt.gov/opinions/23pdf/22-277_d18f.pdf?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+H=
earing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F2%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2=
B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F4%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcus=
tomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) yesterday by the Supreme Court and=
 amounted to a victory for Google=E2=80=99s editorial discretion. So things=
 can certainly change.

In the meantime, Hollywood has its own priorities on the policy front, incl=
uding everything from copyright issues to artificial intelligence. Given th=
is overall landscape, why would Hollywood risk antagonizing lawmakers who
overwhelmingly support the TikTok ban?

Still, I=E2=80=99m frankly puzzled that industry veterans can=E2=80=99t see=
 how a TikTok ban could boomerang and harm Hollywood=E2=80=99s core interes=
ts. What=E2=80=99s to prevent Beijing from retaliating against American int=
ellectual property interests? What=E2=80=99s to stop a future Washington ad=
ministration from using the precedent to curtail Hollywood=E2=80=99s free s=
peech rights? Remember the repercussions Disney faced from Florida Gov. Ron=
 DeSantis after opposing the =E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=99t Say Gay=E2=80=9D bill? =
It wasn=E2=80=99t that long ago! And Donald Trump, who=E2=80=99s leading in=
 the polls, is promising to wield the Justice Department like a personal ha=
mmer. We should know by now how that movie is likely to end.

That=E2=80=99s it for today. Remember, What I=E2=80=99m Hearing is off Thur=
sday. Have a great Fourth, we=E2=80=99ll see you Monday.

Matt

