=80=99s books and records, Paramount=E2=80=99s lawyers at Simpson Thacher c=
ounter that the company is entitled to some =E2=80=9Cbusiness strategy immu=
nity=E2=80=9D to veil the details of their innermost conversations and prot=
ect potential transactions. They paint Rhode Island as a voyeur, claiming t=
he state =E2=80=9Cseeks a live look into the boardroom during a reportedly =
active deal process, and that is impermissible and potentially harmful to P=
aramount.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>If the trial goes forward, it could offer a rar=
e glimpse into the anatomy and legality of dealmaking almost <i>as it is ha=
ppening</i>, given that a special board committee still needs to approve Re=
dstone=E2=80=99s pact with Ellison. Plus, what unfolds in the courtroom cou=
ld offer a peek at shareholder litigation to come and maybe even influence =
Paramount=E2=80=99s future course.</li><br/><li><i>MSNBC on the
docket</i>: NBCUniversal is also heading to trial, thanks to a quiet June 2=
6 court ruling in Georgia. The plaintiff is Dr. <b>Mahendra Amin</b>, an ob=
stetrician gynecologist who found himself in the crosshairs of an MSNBC sto=
ry after a nurse at an immigration detention center in Irwin County, Georgi=
a, raised the alarm over the high rate of hysterectomies. The whistleblower=
 dubbed Amin the =E2=80=9Cuterus collector.=E2=80=9D <b>Rachel Maddow</b>, =
<b>Chris Hayes</b>, and<b> Nicolle Wallace </b>covered the allegations, whi=
ch were later investigated by a U.S. Senate subcommittee, which found that =
=E2=80=9Cdetainees held by the Department of Homeland Security =E2=80=A6 we=
re subjected to unnecessary, invasive and often nonconsensual gynecological=
 surgical procedures,=E2=80=9D according to Georgia Democratic Sen. <b>Jon =
Ossoff</b>.<br/><br/>In September 2021, Dr. Amin filed a defamation lawsuit=
 against NBC, saying he performed only two medically necessary hysterectomi=
es on immigrant women and demanding $30
million in damages. Lawyers for NBC argued their client is protected by fai=
r report privilege, which gives journalists the right to publish fair and a=
ccurate reports about government proceedings.<br/><br/>Last week, U.S. Dist=
rict Court Judge <b>Lisa Godbey Wood</b> rejected NBC=E2=80=99s contention,=
 ruling that an email from a whistleblower falls short of being part of an =
administrative proceeding. The judge, a <b>George W. Bush</b> appointee, al=
